1️⃣ JSON Query
{
  "entity": "customer",
  "columns": ["segment"],
  "aggregations": [
    {"field": "risk_score", "func": "AVG"}
  ],
  "filters": [
    {"field": "risk_score", "op": ">", "value": 70}
  ],
  "group_by": ["segment"],
  "sort": [{"field":"segment","dir":"ASC"}],
  "limit": 100
}

Goal: SQL equivalent:

SELECT segment, AVG(risk_score) AS avg_risk_score
FROM customer
WHERE risk_score > 70
GROUP BY segment
ORDER BY segment ASC
LIMIT 100;
2️⃣ How jOOQ Helps

jOOQ allows you to build this dynamically using its DSL API:

User-defined fields – columns or calculated expressions.
Dynamic filters – based on JSON “filters.”
Aggregations – like AVG, SUM, COUNT.
Group by & order by – fully type-safe.
Limit – standard SQL.

All without manually concatenating strings.

3️⃣ Example in jOOQ (Java)
import static org.jooq.impl.DSL.*;
import org.jooq.*;
import org.jooq.impl.DSL;

DSLContext create = DSL.using(connection, SQLDialect.POSTGRES);

// Table reference
Table<?> CUSTOMER = table(name("customer"));

// Columns
Field<String> segmentField = field(name("segment"), String.class);
Field<Integer> riskScoreField = field(name("risk_score"), Integer.class);

// Aggregation
Field<Double> avgRiskScore = riskScoreField.avg().as("avg_risk_score");

// Filter
Condition filter = riskScoreField.gt(70);

// Build the query
ResultQuery<?> query = create.select(segmentField, avgRiskScore)
    .from(CUSTOMER)
    .where(filter)
    .groupBy(segmentField)
    .orderBy(segmentField.asc())
    .limit(100);

// Execute
List<Record> results = query.fetch();
4️⃣ Notes
Dynamic columns & aggregations:
You can loop through the JSON columns and aggregations array, building Field<?> objects on the fly.
Dynamic filters:
Use a helper method to parse op (>, <, =, IN) and generate a jOOQ Condition.
Condition buildCondition(Field<?> field, String op, Object value) {
    switch(op) {
        case ">": return field.gt(value);
        case "<": return field.lt(value);
        case "=": return field.eq(value);
        default: throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unsupported op: " + op);
    }
}
Type-safe vs dynamic:
If you pre-generate jOOQ classes using codegen, you get full type-safety.
If the fields come dynamically from JSON, you can use DSL.field(name("column_name")) — slightly less type-safe but fully dynamic.

